Events.html: 42 BC – Roman Republican civil wars: Second Battle of Philippi – Mark Antony and Octavian decisively defeat Brutus's army. Brutus commits suicide.

Events.html: 502 – The Synodus Palmaris, called by Gothic king Theodoric the Great, discharges Pope Symmachus of all charges, thus ending the schism of Antipope Laurentius.

Events.html: 1157 – The Battle of Grathe Heath ends the civil war in Denmark. King Sweyn III is killed and Valdemar I restores the country.

Events.html: 1295 – The first treaty forming the Auld Alliance between Scotland and France against England is signed in Paris.

Events.html: 1641 – Outbreak of the Irish Rebellion of 1641.

Events.html: 1642 – Battle of Edgehill: First major battle of the First English Civil War.
Events.text: Battle of Edgehill: First major battle of the First English Civil War.

Events.html: 1694 – British/American colonial forces, led by Sir William Phipps, fail to seize Quebec from the French.

Events.html: 1739 – War of Jenkins' Ear starts: British Prime Minister, Robert Walpole, reluctantly declares war on Spain.
Events.text: War of Jenkins' Ear starts: British Prime Minister, Robert Walpole, reluctantly declares war on Spain.

Events.html: 1812 – Claude François de Malet, a French general, begins a conspiracy to overthrow Napoleon Bonaparte, claiming that the Emperor died in Russia and that he is now the commandant of Paris.

Events.html: 1850 – The first National Women's Rights Convention begins in Worcester, Massachusetts, United States.
Events.text: The first National Women's Rights Convention begins in Worcester, Massachusetts, United States.

Events.html: 1861 – U.S. President Abraham Lincoln suspends the writ of habeas corpus in Washington, D.C., for all military-related cases.

Events.html: 1864 – American Civil War: Battle of Westport – Union forces under General Samuel R. Curtis defeat Confederate troops led by General Sterling Price at Westport, near Kansas City.
Events.text: American Civil War: Battle of Westport – Union forces under General Samuel R. Curtis defeat Confederate troops led by General Sterling Price at Westport, near Kansas City.

Events.html: 1867 – 72 Senators are summoned by Royal Proclamation to serve as the first members of the Canadian Senate.

Events.html: 1870 – Franco-Prussian War: the Siege of Metz concludes with a decisive Prussian victory.
Events.text: Franco-Prussian War: the Siege of Metz concludes with a decisive Prussian victory.

Events.html: 1906 – Alberto Santos-Dumont flies an airplane in the first heavier-than-air flight in Europe at Champs de Bagatelle, Paris, France.

Events.html: 1911 – First use of aircraft in war: An Italian pilot takes off from Libya to observe Turkish army lines during the Turco-Italian War.

Events.html: 1912 – First Balkan War: The Battle of Kumanovo between the Serbian and Ottoman armies begins.
Events.text: First Balkan War: The Battle of Kumanovo between the Serbian and Ottoman armies begins.

Events.html: 1915 – Woman's suffrage: In New York City, 25,000-33,000 women march on Fifth Avenue to advocate their right to vote.

Events.html: 1917 – Lenin calls for the October Revolution.

Events.html: 1929 – Great Depression: After a steady decline in stock market prices since a peak in September, the New York Stock Exchange begins to show signs of panic.

Events.html: 1935 – Dutch Schultz, Abe Landau, Otto Berman, and Bernard "Lulu" Rosencrantz are fatally shot at a saloon in Newark, New Jersey in what will become known as The Chophouse Massacre.
Events.text: Dutch Schultz, Abe Landau, Otto Berman, and Bernard "Lulu" Rosencrantz are fatally shot at a saloon in Newark, New Jersey in what will become known as The Chophouse Massacre.

Events.html: 1939 – The Japanese Mitsubishi G4M twin-engine "Betty" Bomber makes its maiden flight.
Events.text: The Japanese Mitsubishi G4M twin-engine "Betty" Bomber makes its maiden flight.

Events.html: 1941 – World War II: Field Marshal Georgy Zhukov takes command of Red Army operations to prevent the further advance into Russia of German forces and to prevent the Wehrmacht from capturing Moscow.

Events.html: 1942 – World War II: Second Battle of El Alamein: – At El Alamein in northern Egypt, the British Eighth Army under Field Marshal Montgomery begins a critical offensive to expel the Axis armies from Egypt.

Events.html: 1942 – All 12 passengers and crewmen aboard an American Airlines DC-3 airliner are killed when it is struck by a U.S. Army Air Forces bomber near Palm Springs, California. Amongst the victims is award-winning composer and songwriter Ralph Rainger ("Thanks for the Memory", "Love in Bloom", "Blue Hawaii").

Events.html: 1956 – Thousands of Hungarians protest against the government and Soviet occupation. (The Hungarian Revolution is crushed on November 4).

Events.html: 1958 – The Springhill Mine Bump – An underground earthquake traps 174 miners in the No. 2 colliery at Springhill, Nova Scotia, the deepest coal mine in North America at the time. By November 1, rescuers from around the world had dug out 100 of the victims, marking the death toll at 74.

Events.html: 1958 – The Smurfs, a fictional race of blue dwarves, later popularized in a Hanna-Barbera animated cartoon series, appear for the first time in the story La flute à six schtroumpfs, a Johan and Peewit adventure by Peyo, which is serialized in the weekly Spirou magazine.

Events.html: 1965 – Vietnam War: The 1st Cavalry Division (United States) (Airmobile), in conjunction with South Vietnamese forces, launches a new operation seeking to destroy North Vietnamese forces in Pleiku in the II Corps Tactical Zone (the Central Highlands).

Events.html: 1970 – Gary Gabelich sets a land speed record in a rocket-powered automobile called the Blue Flame, fueled with natural gas.

Events.html: 1972 – Operation Linebacker, a US bombing campaign against North Vietnam in response to its Easter Offensive, ends after five months.
Events.text: Operation Linebacker, a US bombing campaign against North Vietnam in response to its Easter Offensive, ends after five months.

Events.html: 1983 – Lebanon Civil War: The U.S. Marines barracks in Beirut is hit by a truck bomb, killing 241 U.S. military personnel. A French army barracks in Lebanon is also hit that same morning, killing 58 troops.
